	publication_stage = {Final},
	type = {Article},
	abstract = {Planetary regolith sampling is essential to deep space exploration missions, motivating researchers to develop innovative sampling techniques for efficient regolith sample acquisition. The Multi-string and Wireline-coring Drilling Robot (MWDR) for planetary regolith sampling is a bottom-hole continuous sampling technology that can efficiently and safely perform deep drilling on extraterrestrial bodies and rapidly obtain bottom samples through a wireline, eliminating the need for astronaut operations. This paper presents the design considerations and development process of an MWDR planetary regolith sampling, from conceptual design to prototype testing, aimed at achieving automatic deep regolith sampling. First, the paper outlines the essential functions of the MWDR based on the requirements for automatic regolith sampling and describes the components that fulfill these functions. Next, the mechanisms and control system of a novel MWDR are proposed to perform automatic regolith sampling tasks, including drilling components for penetration, rotation, and clamping motions, a manipulation component for grabbing and transferring multiple drill tools, and a coring component for collecting regolith samples. A feasible drilling and sampling strategy is then developed, with detailed motion planning for each mechanism to coordinate their movements. Finally, an experimental prototype is developed to conduct automatic drilling tests, validating the functionality of the proposed mechanism system for the MWDR. © 2025 COSPAR},
